Certain preferred embodiments of the present invention will be described in greater detail with reference to the accompanying sheets of drawings, in which:


FIG. 1 is a block diagram showing a general organization of an electric power steering apparatus for an automotive vehicle according to a preferred embodiment of the present invention;


FIG. 2 is a functional block diagram of a control unit employed in the electric power steering apparatus of FIG. 1;


FIG. 3 is a block diagram showing details of a non-steady state detector section in the control unit of FIG. 2;


FIG. 4 is a block diagram showing a modification of the control unit in the inventive electric steering apparatus;


FIG. 5 is a block diagram showing another modification of the control unit in the inventive electric steering apparatus;


FIG. 6 is a block diagram showing still another modification of the control unit in the inventive electric steering apparatus;


FIG. 7 is a graph showing a characteristic control curve of a target motor current signal versus steering torque with vehicle velocities as parameters;


FIG. 8 is a graph showing a characteristic control curve of a modification amount versus a difference between slip angles of front and rear wheels of the vehicle;


FIG. 9 is a graph showing a characteristic control curve of a friction modification coefficient versus a ratio of a yaw rate to a steering angle;


FIG. 10 is a graph showing a characteristic control curve of tire-to-steering-wheel torque versus a steering angle employed in the present invention; and


FIG. 11 is a graph showing a typical relationship between the steering angle and the tire-to-steering-wheel torque in a conventional electric power steering apparatus.
